### Tested versions

Reproducible: v4.4.stable.mono.official [4c311cbee]
Not reproducible: v4.4.stable.official [4c311cbee]

### System information

Godot v4.4.stable.mono - Windows 10 (build 19044) - Multi-window, 2 monitors - Vulkan (Forward+) - dedicated NVIDIA GeForce RTX 3060 Laptop GPU (NVIDIA; 32.0.15.7270) - AMD Ryzen 9 5900HS with Radeon Graphics (16 threads)

### Issue description

If a project has many `gdignore`d files, the editor will freeze for a long time when clicking the `Android` export template button.

https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/dd8ff601-0711-4c5e-8a80-6c84085453f9

### Steps to reproduce

1. Download the MRP
2. Open the project with godot 4.4 mono version
3. Build the C# project
4. Restart the project
5. Open the export menu
6. Click the Android export template
7. Observe the issue

### Minimal reproduction project (MRP)

> **Note**
> Since GitHub has a size limit, I have to lower the count of the gdignored files to 30,000; the actual MRP contains 1,000,000 random binary files, each with a Guid as the file content.

[mrp_slowloadtime.zip](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/19296449/mrp_slowloadtime.zip)

You may procedurally generate these files by the following code:

```csharp
const int files = 1_000_000;

var task = new List<Task>(files);

for (var i = 0; i < files; i++)
{
    var localI = i;
    task.Add(
        Task.Run(
            async () =>
            {
                var randomPayload = Guid.NewGuid().ToByteArray();
                var fileStream = File.Create($@"PATH-TO-THE-MRP\IgnoredDir\RandomFile-{localI:00000}", randomPayload.Length);
                await fileStream.WriteAsync(randomPayload);
                await fileStream.DisposeAsync();
            }
        )
    );
}

await Task.WhenAll(task);
```

### Tested versions

- Reproducible in v4.4.stable.steam [4c311cbee]

### System information

Godot v4.4.stable (4c311cbee) - Windows 10 (build 19045) - Multi-window, 3 monitors - Vulkan (Forward+) - dedicated NVIDIA GeForce RTX 2070 SUPER (NVIDIA; 32.0.15.6636) - AMD Ryzen 5 3600 6-Core Processor (12 threads)

### Issue description

Using fit_margin does not work with texture sampling using the UV of the CanvasGroup. When doing so, zooming on and out introduces some offset.

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/caa95c27-ef9c-45a5-b358-e51ec55999dc)

### Steps to reproduce

In any project:

- Create CanvasGroup
- Add Sprite2D to the CanvasGroup
- Add a ShaderMaterial to the CanvasGroup ([using the custom shader described in the docs](https://docs.godotengine.org/en/stable/classes/class_canvasgroup.html#description))
- Set `fit_margin` to any bigger value (200px for example)
- Sample any texture with the UV, eg:

```glsl
shader_type canvas_item;
render_mode unshaded;

uniform sampler2D noise_texture;
uniform sampler2D screen_texture : hint_screen_texture, repeat_disable, filter_nearest;

void fragment() {
	vec4 noise = texture(noise_texture, UV, 0.);
	vec4 c = texture(screen_texture, SCREEN_UV, 0.0);
	if (c.a > 0.0001) c.rgb /= c.a;
	if(noise.r > 0.5) c.a = 0.;
	COLOR *= c;
}

```

Now, when changing the zoom, the UV no longer behaves as expected.



### Minimal reproduction project (MRP)

Open `test_scene.tscn` in this project:

[canvasgroupfitmargin_2025-03-16_17-52-51.zip](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/19273480/canvasgroupfitmargin_2025-03-16_17-52-51.zip)
